attributes.body:
I didn't even really know about Chicama until Cassie suggested we visit. I had heard that the longest left point break in the world was in Peru, but didn't know it went by the name Chicama until I was already on my way. I left most of my stuff in Huanchaco to keep things simple, and hit the road.

It's a really funny small town. There's really not a lot to do there, unless you surf, in which case, there's tons to do. Time out of the water is generally spent eating to restore enough energy to get back into the water. The only people to visit were surfers, and likewise, it was only surfers at the El Hombre Hostal There was a swell on the way so, there were a bunch of people all getting excited and coming to park on the cliff and watch as though it could all change any second, and some of them just to bow down in appreciation of this glorious wave.

I had a few nice surf sessions. It was a really great place to see some truly great surfers at work. Almost every wave had someone on it, and yet somehow there still seemed to be waves to go around.

On the way out of town we decided to get a little lost and take some roads that we weren't entirely sure were there, and had some fun getting lost.

photos.title: Random City
photos.description: A stop to get directions on the way back to Huanchaco... Very random little village with nothing around it but cane fields.

photos.title: Turning Around
photos.description: The track got really sandy and we started sliding around and decided to try a different road when we encountered a water crossing.

photos.title: Chicama Point
photos.description: That's the point way out there.

photos.title: Cory gets Weird
photos.description: When you're out in the desert on a bike with no name, things get weird, you can't remember your name.

photos.title: Beach Lines
photos.description: Cassie got some great photos, this is one of them.

photos.title: Dead Dolphin
photos.description: This dolphin was a real stinker, every time we walked by I held my breath. Not sure how or why it died, but there it was, left to nature for cleanup.

photos.title: Sedimentary Cliffs Chicama
photos.description: Along the beach, you can look up at these.

photos.title: Fallen Rock
photos.description: You can see where that large rock once fell, I'm sure it was an exciting moment in geology.

photos.title: Surfer
photos.description: And the wave goes on and on.

photos.title: Chicama Late Afternoon
photos.description: This is on the walk out to the point, I think it must have taken about 10 minutes to get way out there by foot.

photos.title: Chicama Sunset from Hostel
photos.description: Here's the view from the hostel in the evening. Not bad at all.

photos.title: Cassie with Ceviche
photos.description: I really love ceviche. Here it's served with some yucca, and potatoes. Even the vegetarian liked it.

photos.title: Chicama Cliff Panorama
photos.description: This gives you more of an idea of the scale of the length of this wave.

photos.title: Mining Company Property
photos.description: This is just above the wave. Looks like I could just ride out into the desert and get lost out here.
